Documentation

Project Name: Arcane Engine – Retro-Style 2.5D FPS Sub-Engine for Unity

Project Fork: CoreArcane

Project Version: 0.5.0

License: MIT

Thank you for downloading this project, it is an ongoing passion project started during the Covid-19 lockdowns (started on the 24th of July 2020, but planned for longer), and was built to address the lack of available robust free, and open-source retro FPS projects akin to the Build Engine.

Please note, this is an ongoing project and is still missing many features that are present in the Build engine, and other games and engines from the time. If you feel that these features are being added too slowly to this project, and have the skills to add them, please feel free to create a new fork.

This documentation is to help you regarding setup and customisation. Please read through the documentation carefully to understand how this project is made and how to edit this properly.

Requirements

You will need the following to use this project:

  1. A computer with a modern operating system (this project was built and tested on Windows 10 64-bit)
  2. Unity 5+ (this project was built using Unity 5.6.7f1 and has been tested with 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020, and 2021)
  3. The patience to read the documentation (I have done my best to make this as user-friendly as possible)

Before changing anything, I HIGHLY recommend you read this documentation, or watch some of the videos available online (links below). No support is provided for faulty customization.

Getting Started

It is always recommended that you import this engine into a blank/new project in Unity, and then import any assets you need and build your game from there, this reduces the risk of conflicts in code, and makes it easier to manage your project.

One of the first things you’ll want to do is open up one of the demo scenes with gameplay (not the menu) and test out the handling, controls, and rendering to see if any settings inside either Unity (Color Space, Graphics) or Arcane’s Manager need changing.

If you do need to change any part of Arcane, such as player handling, or actions, enemy behaviours, or world settings, such as environmental interaction settings, these can be found in the ‘Manager‘ tab of the Arcane Manager, which can be accessed by clicking ‘Arcane Engine/Manager‘ in the Unity editor, or by using the shortcut Ctrl+Alt+A.

To change the controls used in the engine, use the ‘Controls‘ tab of the Arcane Manager instead of Unity’s built-in Input editor, as this is not used.

The editing of existing weapons or creation of new ones is achieved through the Weapon Editor which can be opened either by clicking ‘Arcane Engine/Weapon Editor‘ or by clicking the ‘Weapon Editor‘ button in the top bar of the Arcane Manager.

Tools for adding Arcane-related objects to the scene can be found under ‘Arcane Engine/Creator‘, many can be edited or tailored further from the Unity editor Inspector panel.

If you would prefer to follow an in-depth series of video tutorials on setup, please watch our video series on the Arcane Engine.

Keyboard Shortcuts

Action Shortcut
Engine Manager Ctrl+Alt+A
Creator Ctrl+Alt+C
Weapons Editor Ctrl+Alt+W
Loadout Editor Ctrl+Alt+X
Enemy Editor Ctrl+Alt+E
Scene History Ctrl+Alt+S
Deselect Objects Ctrl+Alt+D
Toggle Labels Ctrl+Alt+L
Toggle Arcane Transform Ctrl+Alt+T

Home Tab

The ‘Home Tab‘ displays a basic overview and checklist of recommended/required elements.

This tab also contains a check to see if the essential settings (prefs) file has been loaded, and handy buttons to quickly add any missing layers with a single click.

Manager Tab

The ‘Manager Tab‘ is where the majority of back-end engine settings can be found.

This includes settings such as player movement speed, default look speed, jump height, action speeds, general behaviours for both players and enemies, and other attributes.

If you need to change any of these settings for any reason, it is best to do this in the ‘Manager‘ rather than altering the Arcane Engine’s code, as these settings may be used in multiple areas and is not undone when Arcane is updated, they can also be set up to be edited using in-game settings.

These settings do not always pertain to things such as world units, and information on what these variables mean (and their defaults) can be found below them in their respective help boxes.

Controls Tab

The ‘Controls Tab‘ is where default controls for your game are set.

This includes basic movement, as well as combat controls, and alternative keys for several actions.

In this tab, you can either select keys from the dropdown lists, or click on the button to the right of the dropdown, then press the desired key (but this is only available for normal keys, and does not work with modifier keys (Ctrl, Alt, Shift), mouse clicks, or controllers, which will need to be selected from the dropdowns).

Unlike the ‘Manager Tab‘, the settings found in the ‘Controls Tab‘ have individual reset buttons, which return the value back to their engine defaults. Hovering over this button will notify you what that default is.

Alternative keys are available for many actions that are normally assigned to the mouse, as many older retro shooters do not use the mouse. These keys include looking up/down, turning left/right, and weapon fire keys.

For more information on how to use this, please click the green question mark button in the top-right of the ‘Controls Tab‘.

About Tab

Pretty self-explanatory…

The ‘About Tab‘ displays information about Arcane, including the fork, author, and version.

It also contains fun milestones on the project, which no one cares about but me.

Creator

Pretty self-explanatory…

For the most part, the ‘Creator Window‘ is your one-stop shop for placing Arcane-related objects within the editor scene.

This window allows for the placing of objects like Player Start, Game Manager, Pickups, Kill Boxes, Switches, Water, Colliders and Triggers, Enemy Spawners, and Level Ends with a couple of clicks.

Weapon Editor

The ‘Weapon Editor‘ window allows for the creation/editing of weapon files.

This is where attributes like weapon damage, shortcut keys, reload speeds, max magazine sizes and capacities are set.

Attributes such as weapon prefab, crosshair presets, weapon positions, muzzle flash location, and audio files are set within the ‘Game Manager‘ component.

Loadout Editor

The ‘Loadout Editor‘ window allows you to adjust the order of your weapons loadout and export them to their own file for use in the ‘Game Manager‘ component.

While this is completely optional, it greatly helps workflow and organisation if you have multiple loadouts for different scenes.

This window allows you to view your loadouts in a reorderable list in which you can swap in and out weapon files created in the ‘Weapons Editor‘ window, then load them seamlessly into the ‘Game Manager‘ component.

Your finalised loadout can also be reordered from the ‘Game Manager‘ component, within the ‘Weapon Order‘ foldout.

Enemy Editor

Similarly to the ‘Weapons Editor‘, the ‘Enemy Editor‘ window allows you to create or edit enemy attributes, including attack type, health, fire rate, and damage per hit.

These files are then used within the ‘Enemy Spawner‘ component, along with an enemy model prefab to create an enemy with those characteristics.

Scene History

The ‘Scene History‘ window is a basic application to build a list of scenes visited while the window is open.

This can allow you to seamlessly and painlessly switch between scenes using buttons on the fly, and help you keep track of what you’re doing, where you’re doing it, and keep your workspace more organised.

Please note, this window must be OPEN to register scenes opened.

Attributions

The Arcane Engine uses a small number of free third-party assets to function (which are supplied with the engine).

Information on what these are, their respective authors and what they are used for, can be found within the Engine Manager’s Documentation tab, under ‘Attributions‘.
